Certainly! Below is a simple HTML web app that serves as an advanced German language trainer. It has embedded CSS and JavaScript for styling and functionality. You can copy and paste the entire code into a `.html` file and open it in your web browser.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="de">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Advanced German Language Trainer</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
            color: #333;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 20px;
        }
        h1 {
            text-align: center;
        }
        .container {
            max-width: 800px;
            margin: 0 auto;
            background: #fff;
            padding: 20px;
            border-radius: 5px;
            box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0,0,0,0.1);
        }
        .question {
            margin: 20px 0;
            font-size: 1.2em;
        }
        .input-area {
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            margin-top: 10px;
        }
        input[type="text"] {
            padding: 10px;
            width: 70%;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }
        button {
            padding: 10px 15px;
            margin-left: 10px;
            border: none;
            background-color: #007BFF;
            color: white;
            border-radius: 5px;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        button:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }
        .result {
            margin-top: 20px;
            font-weight: bold;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="container">
        <h1>German Language Trainer</h1>
        <div class="question" id="question"></div>
        <div class="input-area">
            <input type="text" id="userAnswer" placeholder="Geben Sie Ihre Antwort ein...">
            <button onclick="checkAnswer()">Antwort Ã¼berprÃ¼fen</button>
        </div>
        <div class="result" id="result"></div>
    </div>

    <script>
        const questions = [
            { prompt: "Was ist das Gegenteil von 'warm'?", answer: "kalt" },
            { prompt: "Wie sagt man 'Hello' auf Deutsch?", answer: "Hallo" },
            { prompt: "Was ist die Hauptstadt von Deutschland?", answer: "Berlin" },
            { prompt: "VervollstÃ¤ndigen Sie den Satz: 'Ich ___ (sein) ein Lehrer.'", answer: "bin" },
            { prompt: "Was bedeutet 'Buch' auf Englisch?", answer: "book" }
        ];

        let currentQuestionIndex = 0;

        function loadQuestion() {
            const questionElement = document.getElementById('question');
            questionElement.innerHTML = questions[currentQuestionIndex].prompt;
        }

        function checkAnswer() {
            const userAnswer = document.getElementById('userAnswer').value.toLowerCase().trim();
            const resultElement = document.getElementById('result');
            const correctAnswer = questions[currentQuestionIndex].answer.toLowerCase();

            if (userAnswer === correctAnswer) {
                resultElement.innerHTML = "Korrekt! ðŸŽ‰";
            } else {
                resultElement.innerHTML = `Falsch! Die richtige Antwort ist: ${correctAnswer}.`;
            }
            document.getElementById('userAnswer').value = '';
            currentQuestionIndex = (currentQuestionIndex + 1) % questions.length; // Loop through questions
            loadQuestion();
        }

        window.onload = loadQuestion; // Load first question
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
- **HTML Structure**: The code creates a simple layout with a title, a question display area, an input box for the user's answer, and a button to check the answer.
- **CSS Styles**: The styling is embedded to make the app visually appealing with a clean layout, centered content, and button hover effects.
- **JavaScript Functionality**: The JS code manages the questions and answers and checks the user's input against correct answers. It will show feedback on whether the answer was correct or not, and move to the next question after each attempt.

You can expand upon this code by adding more questions, improving the UI, or adding more features as needed.
